  "prompt": "How did the ring come to Sauron?",
  "response": "In J.R.R. Tolkien's Middle-earth legendarium, the One Ring was forged by Sauron during the Second Age. Sauron, who was a powerful Maia and servant of Morgoth, created the Ring to dominate and control the other Rings of Power that had been made by the Elves. He intended the One Ring to enhance his own power and to corrupt its bearers.\n\nThe process began in the elven realm of Eregion, where Sauron, disguised as Annatar, the \"Lord of Gifts,\" deceived the Elven smiths, particularly Celebrimbor, into forging the Rings of Power. While the Elves crafted their rings, Sauron secretly forged the One Ring in the fires of Mount Doom in Mordor.\n\nAfter he completed the Ring, Sauron put it on, which revealed his presence to the other Rings' bearers. This act allowed him to exert control over their wielders, most notably the seven Dwarven Rings and the nine Rings given to Men, leading to their eventual corruption.\n\nSauron wielded the One Ring for centuries until it was taken from him in the War of the Last Alliance of Elves and Men. He was defeated by Isildur, who cut the Ring from Sauron's hand with the broken sword Narsil. However, Isildur's eventual demise led to the Ring being lost for many ages until it was found by Gollum and later came into the possession of Frodo Baggins, setting the stage for the events of \"The Hobbit\" and \"The Lord of the Rings.\"",
